orig=Meteorology of Saint John - Temperature. The mean temperature of May was about 1.5  below that of 1864, and nearly a quarter of a degree below the average of 15 years. The highest reading of the thermometer was 67  on the 29th, and the or lowest 32  on the 8th. On this latter morning ice nearly an eighth of an inch thick, was formed in exposed places in the vicinity of the City. Last year the highest reading of the thermometer in May was 78  on the 28th, and the extreme range for the month 35. The greatest oscillation in one day was 19 (8th) and the average for the month 9.8 -- Last year the maximum oscillation was 27, and the monthly mean 12.26. The average of the latter for 5 years is 11.45.   Looking at the weekly temperatures--the first was 2.7 colder than in 1864, the second 2.83, and the  third 2.75, while the fourth was 1.6 warmer. For the various hours of observations the mean readings for this year and last were as follows: ----  1865 [In degrees]  6am: 44.50 10am: 49.84 2pm: 52.68 6pm: 50.10 10pm: 46.77 --- 1864 [In degrees]  6am: 44.19 10am: 51.30 2pm: 55.87 6pm: 49.55 10pm: 47.19 mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=Wind -- The wind was light for the whole month, and was E. to S.W. 21 days, and W. to N.E. 10 days. The most prevalent was S.W May 1864, [which] had 22 days of Southerly weather, and the average for 16 years is about 21% days.   ---------     Ozone was much more plentiful than in any other of the Spring months, and in this respect agreed with the observations of other years. The highest notation was 9.0, with a fresh N.E. wind during the night of the 3rd. Its day mean was 2.05, and its night 2.7. Last year The former was 1.4, and the latter 2.8. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=Precipitation. The most notable meteorological feature of May was its great and very unusual rain-fall, which surpassed by nearly 100% any corresponding month's record for the last 15  years at least. It began with a drenching ruin, and with brief intermissions continued wet to near its close. The highest month's rain on record (for May) since 1850, is 5.4 inch, and the average for the same period (leaving out this year's) [is] 3.07 inch; but this year the May rain was no less than 10.33 inch. It rained on 12 days and 14 nights. The highest  day rain was 1.1 inch on the 9th, and the night rain 2 inches on the 23rd. The total day rain measured 4.50 inch, and the nights 5.44 inch. On the morning and forenoon of the 7th we were favoured with about an inch-and-a-half of snow [1.5 inches], which yielded, when melted, about 3-tenths of water. At Bass River, Kent County, as much as 8 inches of snow fell at this time.  The relative periodical falls of rain and melted snow were as follows, for this year and last:  1865 [in inches]  1st  week: 1.885 2nd week: 2.570 3rd week: 0.830 4th week: 5.035  1864 [in inches]  1st  week: 0.635 2nd week: 0.300 3rd week: 0.160 4th week: 0.870  -  Once only since 1850 has any month's rain been greater than for May last, and that was in November, 1854, when the rain and melted snow was upwards 14.5 inch. Perhaps a better idea will be formed of the May rainfall, when it is known to have been equal to 6.4 wine gallons  per square foot, or 280,500 gallons for each acre of surface within the city. If the estimation were made by weight, it would be fully 53lbs. per square foot, or 2,314,000lbs. (1033 tons) per acre. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=Sky.  During the month 5 mornings were clear, 4 days and 7 nights; and 21 mornings, 23 days and 23 nights were wholly clouded. The mean estimated clouding for 8 a. m. Was 7.7; for 2 p. m., 8.1; and for 10 p. m., 7.6. At the same hours 6 mornings were foggy, 4 days and 9 nights.    -----------      Memoranda. - The aurora was seen on 2 nights, and the coast of Nova Scotia on 4 days. On the 17th there was a short thunder-storm that passed to the southward, east of the city On the same day in May, 1864, there was also a thunder-storm. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=Barometer -- The mean pressure of the atmosphere differed little from that of last year and during the month there was no extreme or violent disturbance. The highest reading of the barometer was 30.374 inch on the 19th, and the lowest 29.480 on the 26th. The extreme range  was thus 0.944 inch, In May '64 the highest reading was 30.3 inch on the 16th, and the lowest 29.322 on the 27th. The greatest mean daily range of pressure was 0.415, between the 9th and 10th, but the monthly average was 0.164 inch. The maximum  of mean daily range in May last year was 0.33 inch, and the average for the month 0.109 inch. This latter for 5 years past is 0.172 inch. The tri-daily pressures for this year and last were as follows, corrected for temperature:  ------- 1865 [In inches]:  8am: 29.880 in. 2pm: 29.854 in. 10pm: 029.892 in. Mean: 29.874 in. ------- 1864:  8am: 29.871 in. 2pm: [Illegible] 10pm: 29.867 in. Mean: 29.853 in.  Mean of 5 years: 29.832 in.       -----------     Watery Vapour.-The maximum of watery vapor suspended in the atmosphere was 0.585 inch on the 29th, and the minimum 0.172 in. on the 5th. The lowest relative humidity was 70 per cent on the 19th, and the greatest difference  between the readings of the hygrometric thermometers 7 on the 6th. Last year this latter was 15 , and for the year before 18. The following are the means of the usual tri-daily readings:  Force of Vapour (inches) 8am: 0.303 in. 2pm: 0.343 in. 10pm: 0.316 in. Mean: 0.316 in.  Humidity (%) 8am: 92 2pm: 86 10pm: 93 Mean: 90  The mean elastic force of vapor for May 1864 was 0.308 inch, and of humidity 84%.   ------------ mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=Extraordinary meteor. A meteor of a somewhat strange and extraordinary character was seen from this city about 27 minutes to 11 o'clock [10:33pm] tonight. Notice was first drawn to it by a deep whirring noise, similar to what is heard from a newly projected rocket, and as soon as the eye turned in the direction of this strange sound, a number of small star like specks were observed shooting from a common centre a few degrees south of the zenith. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=It wore this later appearance for about 5 minutes (by the watch) flowing all the while with a bright bluish light. Its shape and colour then began to alter -- the latter changing to a dull red and orange and the former to that of a mammoth fish -- the head, the body, the fins, the tail everything in fact minutely and perfectly outlined. The colour however was not consistent, but oscillated and for some minutes paled and deepened by turn. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=The mercury in the thermometer marked 42 degrees and the mean temperature of the day was 48 degrees. the barometer was unusually low (28.923 inch) and had been so all day. During the evening a number of small meteors were visible, but at a great  istance and without uniformity of motion. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=While the noise continued a thin body of luminous matter was projected northwardly. -- After describing a small part it seemed to be arrested in its progress; but the light remained distinctly visible for at least half an hour after. At first it had a sword like shape and in one or two minutes more that of a huge uptill with its creeping quivering motion. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=While retaining this fish-like shape the head and body appeared to be much more dense and luminous than the tail which was attenuated and of a pale bluish colour. In about 15 minutes from the time it was first seen it began to lose its definite power and at last appeared as a luminous patch of auroral matter floating lazily in the air, but at a great height and with a westward motion. The air was clear and dry, and a strong west wind prevailed (4.0) at the time. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1865-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=Beautiful auroral display. Appeared at first as a quite mass of luminous cloud of a pale bluish colour - shifting along the northern horizon with an elevation of about 30 degrees. After a while form changed and it appeared as two concentric arches: the upper much larger and heavier than the one below. Span NW to East nearly. Quiet and motionless until about 9 o'clock [9pm] when streams of light began to jerk and flow from both in successive broken waves to a point near the zenith. Visible until a late hour in the morning displaying at times a fine variety of colour. - Night clear, calm, and cold. - Barometer high with an inclination to fall. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-01-01_CP.jpg

orig=Barometer.-- Although February had more Southerly weather than in 1866, yet the atmosphere was considerably heavier than in that year. The highest reading of the barometer was 30.73 inch (27th) and the lowest 29.286 inch on the 15th-shewing an extreme oscillation for the month of 1.444 inch. The greatest mean difference of pressure between following days was 0.929 inch (15th and 16th), the least 0.039 (9th and 10th), and the mean for the  month 0.311 inch. In 1865 the maximum reading of the barometer was 30.51 (28th) the extreme range of pressure 1.316, and the mean daily range 0.305 inch. The tri-daily mean readings corrected for temperature were as follows: 1866 [in inches]: 8am: 30.100 2pm: 30.016 10pm: 30.122 Means: 30.094  -----  1865 [in inches]: 8am: 29.872 2pm: 29.834 10pm: 29.875 Means: 29.860  *Means for 6 years: 29.925 inches mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Ozone is never very abundant in this month The highest notation was 6.0, with light W.N.W. wind on the 20th. The day mean was 0.25, and the night 0.82, In 1865 the maximum was 7.0, the day mean 0.28, and the night 0.65. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Temperature.-- The early part of February was excessively cold, yet the mean for the month was 4-10ths above the average, and 1-3 d[ecimals?] of a degree only below that for 1866. The first week was 11.72 colder than the corresponding one last year; but the second was 7.92, and the third 1.5 warmer, while the fourth again was 0.75 colder. The extreme range of temperature was 59 -- the highest reading having been 47 on the 24th, and the lowest reading 12 below zero on the 7th. In 1866 the extreme oscillation was 38 only, but the average is about 53. The greatest change of temperature in one day was 29 on the 17th, and the average for the month 10.2 The warmest day had a mean heat of 43, and the coldest 1.7 below zero. The means for the various hours of observation were as follows for this year and last: 1866 [in degrees]: 6:30am: 19.11 10am: 22.00 2pm: 25.50 6pm: 23.46 10pm: 19.64  ----  1865 [in degrees]: 6:30am: 18.80 10am: 22.07 2pm: 26.50 6pm: 24.53 10pm: 21.64 mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Watery Vapour--The greatest elastic force of vapour, was 0.275 inch, and least humidity 48%. The maximum difference between the wet and dry bulb thermometers being 4 The tri-daily means were as follows: Force Vapour [in inches]: 8am: 0.111 2pm: 0.124 10pm: 0.112 Means: 0.116  ----- Humidity [%]: 8am: 82 2pm: 86  10pm: 85 Means: 84  In 1865 the mean elasticity was 1.102 inch the humidity 76%, and the greatest difference between the thermometers 5. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Wind- The wind was moderate for the whole month, the highest estimated force being 4.0 only. The mean day force was 2.0, and the night :1.5. There were 13 days of Southerly weather and 15 of Northerly Wind- The wind was moderate for the whole month, the highest estimated force being 4.0 only. The  mean day force was 2.0, and the night :1.5. There were 13 days of Southerly weather and 15 of Northerly. Last year had 9 days of Southerly weather, but the average is about 10.5 days. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Sky.- Eight mornings, 11 days and 12 nights were clear, and 15 mornings, 16 days and 14 nights wholly clouded. The mean estimated clouding was for the morning 6.5, for the day 6.4, and for the night 5.3. Two days were foggy. The aurora was seen on 4 nights, and the coast of Nova Scotia on 3 days, without a subsequent storm within 24 hours. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Precipitation.-A very remarkable feature in the meteorology of this month was its precipitation: not, however, as snow, but as rain. --It snowed or rained on 7 days and 5 nights. The snowfall measured 8.00 inches, and yielded 0.46 inch of water. Last year the snowfall was 3.3. Inch only (the lowest on record), and the average of 16 years is 12.9 inch. February, 1863 had 23 inches of snow, which is the highest on record for the period named. The rainfall was unusually great; indeed, there is nothing on record for this month nearly  equal to it; but while this is the case, another peculiarity is the short time in which it fell. In one night (12) 2.6 inch fell, and of this quantity 2 inches fell in less than 6 hours. Another day's rain (19th) measured 1.79 inch, and another (25th) 1.575. As the ground was hard frozen and nearly bare of snow, the floods that followed these storms were sudden and great. The whole fall for the month was 6.99 inch. That for the last year was 2.19, and the average since 1850 is 2.61 inch, this month included.  The comparative periodic falls for this year and last, were as follows, (snow water included): 1866 [in inches]: 1st week: 0.290 2nd week: 2.090 3rd week: 2.635 4th week: 1.625 Totals: 7.450  ----- 1865 [in inches]: 1st week: 0.000 2nd week: 1.195  3rd week: 0.060 4th week: 1.180 Totals: 2.454 mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Barometer.-The barometer had an extreme range of 1.696 inch ; from 29.104 in December to 30.8 inch in January. The mean daily range was 0.299 inch, and the mean pressure deduced from tri-daily observations 30.036, or 0.214 inch higher than for the preceding Winter. The mean Winter pressure of the atmosphere for the last 6 years is about 29.934 inch, or only 3-thousandths of an inch greater than that obtained from the 10 p.m. observations alone. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=WINTER. Temperature.-Our Winter Season, supposed to end with February, had a mean temperature of 19.74, (by observations made at 6 a. m. and 2 p.m.) It ranged from 22 below to 47 above zero. The Winter  before had a mean of 20.94, and the average since 1850 is 21.67. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Watery Vapour.- The mean elastic force of vapour was 0.101 inch--the mean Humidity 80%,  and the greatest difference between the wet and dry bulb thermometers 4. The wind was E. to S. W. 26 days, and W. to N.E. 64 days. Last year had 20 days of Southerly weather, and the average is about 22 3-4 days. The mean ozonic notations for day and night was 0.55, last year it was 0.41. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Sky.- Twenty-six morning, 80 days and 43 nights were clear, and 51 mornings, 48 days and 44 nights wholly clouded. The aurora was seen on 5 nights, and the coast of Nova Scotia on 6 days. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Precipitation.- Rain or snow fell during the Winter Season on 17 days and 18 nights. The snowfall measured 50.55 inch, and yielded 4.97 inch  of water. For the Winter of 1864-5, the snowfall was 53.35 inch, and the average is about 50.32 inch. The rainfall was 9.355 inch, that for last year being 8.86 inch, and the average for 16 years 7.4 inch. The Winter just ended appears to have been wetter than usual, but it will be re- collected that 6.99 inch of rain fell in February alone, and only for this it would have appeared, as it really was for the greater part of the Season, exceedingly dry. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1866-02-01_CP.jpg

orig=Near the easter horizon it was scarcely visible but as it crept towards the zenith it thickened and became as it were more dense: passing westward, however, it again thinned, until near the horizon it was again all but invisible. It may be that the continuous flow westward was only apparent, but earnest watching failed to detect any upward flow from that quarter. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1867-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=Aurora borealis: Visible from an early hour in the morning until far in the night but although the whole northern sky was illuminated with a soft steady light there was nothing unusually attractive until about 10:30pm when a ribbon of light was suddenly seen near the zenith, spanning the sky from ESE to WSW. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1867-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=This isolated arch was singularly strange and beautiful. It had not the altitude the aurora usually has when seen near the zenith nor did it appear to have the same quick jerking motion. To the casual looker it seemed motionless but close observation showed that it was maintained by a continuous flow from the Eastward; this however could only be observed by keeping the eye steadily fixed on one of the many stars seen through and far beyond it. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1867-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=It was visible about 30 minutes and from the low [illegible: portions] in the sky and the night being clear and calm and cloudless, attracted considerable notice. The wind was east and light. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1867-05-01_CP.jpg

orig=At the same time as this was visible in the ENE, faint streams of light were rising from the NW, but they had no peculiar characteristics. They rose slowly until they met what issued from the eastward and completed the arch. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1868-03-01_CP.jpg

orig=The centre or nucleus had a rugged outline and from the wispy way in which its upper forks bent back towards the North, looked as if its progress was impeded by some mysterious power in the successive streams that flowed from it were turned from their upward course by some strange influence and carried towards the north and west. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1868-03-01_CP.jpg

orig=About midnight it presented a very peculiar appearance. Low down, near the horizon (ENE) there was what seemed to be a concentration in nucleus of light from which radiated as from a common centre westward streams of bright auroral light but mired at times with clouds of a greyish hue. These streams did not rise to the zenith, but were deflected towards the NW and formed a series of concentric though somewhat broken arches. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1868-03-01_CP.jpg

orig=Aurora visible from early hour in the evening until far in night. Whole of northern and eastern sky brightly illuminated. Broken pale black cloud skirting horizon. Occasional short sharp pointed streams; brisk and bright. Barometer high: wind east and light. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1868-03-01_CP.jpg

orig=BAROMETER - The barometer showed less atmospheric disturbance for this month than for any corresponding one for some years past, notwithstanding the violent gale which raged during the night of the 4th. The lowest reading (29.322 in.) took place on the last named day, and its highest (30.267 in) on the 26th. The difference between the highest and the lowest readings was 0.945 inches, while in 1868 it was 1.113, and the average is 1.13 inch. The greatest mean difference between two following days (24th and 26th) was 0.477 in, and the least 0.026 [inches], the mean for the month being 0.204 in. The latter in 1868 was 0.241 [inches], and the mean is 0.219 in. The following are the means of the usual tri-daily readings: - 1869 [in inches]: 8am: 29.895 2pm: 29.866 10pm: 29.873 Means: 29.878 --- 1868 [in inches]: 8am: 30.103 2pm: 30.067 10pm: 30.084 Means: 30.085  Avg. 9 years, 29.947 inches. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1869-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=WATERY VAPOUR. - As might be inferred from the extra heat of October, its air had mixed with it a larger share than usual of aqueous vapour. The highest elastic force was 0.541 inches, on the 4th, and the lowest 0.06 in. on the 27th, the average of the former being 0.462 and of the latter 0.093 in. The lowest relative humidity noted was 41% on the 27th, also, and the greatest difference between the wet and dry bulb thermometers 7 degrees on the 20th. The average of minimum humidity for this month is 50%. and maximum difference 7.7.  The tri-daily means were as follows: Force Vapour [in inches]:  8am: 0.293 2pm: 0.321 10pm: 0.278 Means: 0.297 Avg., 8 years: 0.257  ---  Humidity [%] 8am: 88 2pm: 79 10pm: 86 Means: 84 Avg., 8 years: 82 mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: missing|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1869-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=TEMPERATURE - Though the early part of October brought one of the most destructive gales that ever devastated this Province, and the weather prophets would have it that this was but the beginning of grand series of such disasters, happily it turned out otherwise; and so far from the remainder of the month being blustering or unpleasant, it was one of the quietest and finest and warmest known for many years. The temperature of the three first weeks meaned 7.81 above that of the corresponding ones in 1868, and 3.64 above the average for those weeks. A cold spell, however, came with the fourth, and its mean fell 6.81 below the temperature of the same week last year, and 9 below the average since 1860. The several periodic means deduced from bi-daily readings were as follows for this and former years:- --- 1869. [in degrees] 1st week: 54.56 2nd week: 50.19 3rd week: 46.81 4th week: 36.56 --- 1868. [in degrees] 1st week: 48.17 2nd week: 47.00 3rd week: 35.46 4th week: 37.38 --- Avg. 9 years. [in degrees] 1st week: 50.00 2nd week: 47.42 3rd week: 45.23 4th week: 39.50 --- An inspection of the above figures shows that although October had many pleasant characteristics  yet its temperature was somewhat abnormal  in extremes of heat and cold; for while the difference between the means of the first and last weeks was 25 the average is only 0.5 The highest heat recorded during this month was 70 on the 4th. This is 6 above the highest recorded since 1860, but the notes left by the late Mr. Gove show a maximum of 76 in 1851. The minimum of last year was 59 and the average of 9 years is 61.77 The lowest temperature observed for the month was 23[] on the 28th, which is exactly the figure reached in 1868, but 3 below the average minimum. The extreme range for the month was the very unusual one for St. John of 47, or 11 more than in 1868, and the same above the average monthly disturbance; yet the greatest change in one day was only 20, and the mean of daily disturbance 9.52 or nearly one degree less than the average, and 2.16 less than for October last year. The warmest day (4th) had a mean heat of 64, and the coldest (28th) of 28, the former being 7.3 above the warmest day for the same period in 1868, and the latter one degree lower than the lowest mean last year.  The usual hourly readings gave the following results for the month as a whole: --- 1869. [in degrees] 6am: 43.74 10am: 49.45 2pm: 51.13 6pm: 48.45 10pm: 45.03 Mean (6am, 2pm, and 10pm): 46.63 --- 1868. [in degrees] 6am: 37.51 10am: 43.71 2pm: 46.71 6pm: 44.20 10pm: 41.48 Mean (6am, 2pm, and 10pm): 41.90 --- Avg. 9 years. [in degrees] 6am: 41.71 10am: 47.10 2pm: 49.96 6pm: 46.98 10pm: 44.17 Mean (6am, 2pm, and 10pm): 45.28 mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1869-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=PRECIPITATION. - October had 6 days and 8 nights on which rain or snow fell in measurable quantities. The first snow of the season fell on the 19th, but it was the 27th before enough fell to be measured. The fall for the month was only 1.3 inch, and gave when melted one tenth [1/10th] of its bulk of water. The corresponding month last year had 6.93 inches of snow, one inch and hail having fallen as early as the 17th. [Rest of document missing] mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1869-10-01_CP.jpg

orig=Raining all morning sky lighted up a little at 8:30am but soon darkened again. ([At] 2pm) has rained steadily all forenoon: wind backed to SE about noon: blowing fresh and gusty. ([At] 6pm) has rained heavily all afternoon and still continues. ([At] 8pm) rain continues in unabated volume. Very dark wind increasing and veering southward. ([At] 10pm) Fierce wild wind blowing from about SSW in long gusty waves. Still dark; but clouds less dense than during the earlier part of the evening. No rain since about 8:30 o'clock mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1872-11-01_CP.jpg

orig=Light rain between 7 and 8 but rain of last night ended shortly after midnight. There has been, however, a few scuds since. Wind continues very high. ([At] 2pm) wind westerly all forenoon very high and squally with occasional glimpses or bursts of sunshine: overcast at present. ([At] 6pm) the storm has been gradually abating all afternoon, the clouds lightning and the wind becoming less violent, while the Barometer has been rising steadily. ([At] 10pm) The sky is now cloudless and the wind much easier than it was in the afternoon, though it is still blowing strongly. This has had the effect of drying up the ground to a great extent after the heavy rain which preceded it. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1872-11-01_CP.jpg

orig=Wind veered by East and South [SE?] to SW  during the night (of 29th) and blew for a while with great fury. Reached its maximum between 5 and 6 o'clock [5-6am]. Several vessels stranded in Courtenay Bay. Two wrecked on foul ground. 5 out of 7 of a crew belonging to the "Reward" of Nova Scotia drowned. Side walls of Young Mens Christian Association building blown down. Temperature rose during the earlier part of the storm (while the rain fell) 23 degrees or from 20 [degrees] to 43 degrees. When wind got to westward began to fall again. Barometer reached its minimum 29.100 [inches] about 8 o'clock: having fallen 1 inch in 34 hours mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1872-11-01_CP.jpg

orig=STORM: Storm of wind and snow. Began about 2pm and continued until about 10pm. Snow fall 12 inches. Wind NE while storm was heaviest. Changed through N to NW about 8pm. Greatest noted velocity 16 miles per hour; but came at times in strong swelling gusts that doubtless succeeded this considerably. Barometer - began to fall from 29.69in about 8am of 10th and continued until 8pm: whole fall 0.233in in 12 hours. Rose rapidly afterwards. Increase in 12 hours 0.623 inches. mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1873-03-01_CP.jpg

orig=STORM: Wind and snow. Snow began to fall 10:15pm and continued all night. Drifted greatly. Wind shifted from NE to East about 9am of 20th. Remained light and steady all day. Began to quicken about 10pm. Blew heavily from about 12pm (20th) until 9am of 21st. Heaviest from 4[am] to 6am. Abated as the day advanced and at 4pm was quite calm. Began to freshen again about 7pm (21st) and move by S to SW. Remained SW about 24 hours and then veered westward. Barometer at 2pm of 20th marked 30.012 inch, and from this continued to fall until about 4pm of 21st, when it stood at 29.142inches. Whole fall in 20 hours 0.87inches. Recovered slightly during the evening but declined again during the night and marked at 8am of 22nd 29.136in. Weather remained unsettled until about noon of the 22nd. Total snowfall, 8.05inches mno|Local time: daily|QC flag: None|Image File: SaintJohn_USSI-401_M1958_1873-03-01_CP.jpg
